# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: french-navy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] The **1999 East Timorese crisis** began with attacks by pro-Indonesia militia groups on civilians and expanded to general violence throughout the country, centred in the capital Dili.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] The violence intensified after a majority of eligible East Timorese voters voted for independence from Indonesia.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] A Scorched Earth Operation by militia groups destroyed 80% of Dili's infrastructure.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] At least 1,400 civilians are believed to have been murdered both before and after voting.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] A UN-authorized force (INTERFET) consisting mainly of Australian Defence Force personnel was deployed to East Timor to establish and maintain peace.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Independence for East Timor, or even limited regional autonomy, was not allowable under Suharto's New Order.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Notwithstanding Indonesian public opinion in the 1990s occasionally showing begrudging appreciation of the Timorese position, it was widely feared that an independent East Timor would destabilise Indonesian unity.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Renewed United Nations-brokered mediation efforts between Indonesia and Portugal began in early 1997.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] The 1997 Asian financial crisis, however, caused tremendous upheaval in Indonesia and led to Suharto's resignation in May 1998, ending his thirty-year presidency.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Prabowo, by then in command of the powerful Indonesian Strategic Reserve, went into exile in Jordan and military operations in East Timor were costing the bankrupt Indonesian government a million dollars a day.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] The subsequent "*reformasi*" period of relative political openness and transition, included unprecedented debate about Indonesia's relationship with East Timor.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] For the remainder of 1998, discussion forums took place throughout Dili working towards a referendum.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Indonesian Foreign Minister Alatas described plans for phased autonomy leading to possible independence as "all pain, no gain" for Indonesia.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] On 8 June 1998, three weeks after taking office, Habibie, as Suharto's successor, announced that Indonesia would soon offer East Timor a special plan for autonomy.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] In late 1998, the Australian Government of John Howard drafted a letter to Indonesia advising of a change in Australian policy, and advocating a referendum on independence within a decade.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] President Habibie saw such an arrangement as implying "colonial rule" by Indonesia and he decided to call a snap referendum on the issue.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Indonesia and Portugal announced on 5 May 1999 that a vote would be held allowing the people of East Timor to choose between the autonomy plan or independence.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] The vote, to be administered by the United Nations Mission in East Timor (UNAMET), was originally scheduled for 8 August but later postponed until 30 August.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Indonesia also took responsibility for security; this arrangement caused worry in East Timor, but many observers believe that Indonesia would have refused to allow foreign peacekeepers during the vote.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] As groups supporting autonomy and independence began campaigning, a series of pro-integration paramilitary groups of East Timorese began threatening and committing violence around the country.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Alleging pro-independence bias on the part of UNAMET, the groups were seen working with and receiving training from Indonesian soldiers.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Before the May agreement was announced, an April paramilitary attack in Liquiça left dozens of East Timorese dead.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] On 16 May 1999, a gang accompanied by Indonesian troops attacked suspected independence activists in the village of Atara; in June another group attacked a UNAMET office in Maliana.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Indonesian authorities claimed to be helpless to stop what it claimed was violence between rival East Timorese factions, but Ramos-Horta joined many others in scoffing at such notions.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] In February 1999 he said: "Before [Indonesia] withdraws it wants to wreak major havoc and destabilization, as it has always promised.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] As the date of the vote drew near, reports of anti-independence violence continued to accumulate.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] The day of the vote, 30 August 1999, was generally calm and orderly.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] 98.6 per cent of registered voters cast ballots, and on 4 September UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan announced that 78.5 per cent of the votes had been cast for independence.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Brought up on the "New Order"'s insistence that the East Timorese supported integration, Indonesians were either shocked or incredulous that the East Timorese had voted against being part of Indonesia.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Many accepted media stories blaming the supervising United Nations and Australia who had pressured Habibie for a resolution.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] As UNAMET staff returned to Dili following the ballot, towns began to be systematically razed.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Within hours of the results, paramilitary groups had begun attacking people and setting fires around the capital Dili.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Foreign journalists and election observers fled, and tens of thousands of East Timorese took to the mountains.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Indonesian Muslim gangs attacked Dili's Catholic Diocese building, killing two dozen people; the next day, the headquarters of the ICRC was attacked and burned to the ground.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Almost one hundred people were killed later in Suai, and reports of similar massacres poured in from around East Timor.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] The vast majority of the UN staff locked down in their Dili compound, which had been flooded with refugees, refused to evacuate unless the refugees were withdrawn as well, insisting they would rather die at the hands of the paramilitary groups.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] At the same time, Indonesian troops and paramilitary gangs forced over 200,000 people into West Timor, into camps described by Human Rights Watch as "deplorable conditions".
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] After several weeks the Australian Government offered to allow the refugees in the UN compound along with the UN staff to be evacuated to Darwin, and all the refugees and all except four UN staff were evacuated.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] When a UN delegation arrived in Jakarta on 8 September, they were told by Habibie that reports of bloodshed in East Timor were "fantasies" and "lies".
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] General Wiranto of the Indonesian military insisted that his soldiers had the situation under control, and later expressed his emotion for East Timor by singing the 1975 hit song "Feelings" at an event for military wives.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Australia provided the largest contingent of troops, hardware and equipment for the INTERFET operation—5,500 personnel at its peak—followed by New Zealand.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] New Zealand's contribution peaked at 1,200 personnel.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] It was New Zealand's largest overseas military deployment since the Korean War.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Eventually, 22 nations contributed to INTERFET, which grew to over 11,500 strong.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Another 40 nations joined UNTAET as either contributing military personnel or civilian police officers.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Australia was refused US ground troops but was able to secure vital support for airlift, logistics, specialised intelligence, over the horizon deterrence, and "diplomatic muscle".
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Japan who was prevented by law from sending troops provided significant financial funding of a US$100 million.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Participants were awarded the International Force East Timor Medal by the Australian Government.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] As lead nation Australia provided logistic support for a number of other nations in addition to its own requirements.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Meanwhile, the 9th Force Support Battalion was deployed to Darwin to provide additional support, and later rotated with 10 FSB in East Timor.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Despite the proximity of considerable civilian and military infrastructure in Darwin, the provision of this support proved a major challenge for Australia, which had not been required to provide full logistic support for a deployed force since the Second World War.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Reductions in defence spending over the previous decade had led to the run-down of its logistic support force, resulting in the requirement to quickly implement a range of ad hoc measures to overcome these shortfalls.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] The violence was met with widespread public anger in Australia, Portugal and elsewhere and activists in Portugal, Australia, the United States and other nations pressured their governments to take action.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Australian Prime Minister John Howard consulted United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan and lobbied U.S.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] President Bill Clinton to support an Australian-led international peacekeeping force to enter East Timor to end the violence.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] The United States offered crucial logistical and intelligence resources and an "over-horizon" deterrent presence, but did not commit forces to the operation.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Indonesia, in dire economic straits, relented.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Habibie announced on 12 September that Indonesia would withdraw its soldiers and allow an Australian-led international peacekeeping force to enter East Timor.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] They murdered dozens of innocent and unarmed villagers along the way and, near Dili, killed one journalist and attempted to kill two more.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] INTERFET then launched an operation to secure the last part of the country the Oecussi Enclave.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] On 22 October 1999, the SASR conducted an air insertion in Black Hawk helicopters at Port Makasa in the enclave together with an hour later an amphibious landing from a Navy landing craft with their vehicles.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] The night before Australian Navy Clearance divers from HMAS *Success* had conducted a clandestine beach reconnaissance of the amphibious landing area.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] The International Force for East Timor, or INTERFET, under the command of Australian Major General Peter Cosgrove, entered Dili on 20 September and by 31 October the last Indonesian troops had left East Timor.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] The arrival of thousands of international troops in East Timor caused the militia to flee across the border into Indonesia, whence sporadic cross-border raids by the militia against INTERFET forces were conducted.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] The United Nations Transitional Administration in East Timor (UNTAET) was established at the end of October and administered the region for two years.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Control of the nation was turned over to the Government of East Timor and independence was declared on 20 May 2002.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] On 27 September of the same year, East Timor joined the United Nations as its 191st member state.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] The bulk of the military forces of INTERFET were Australian.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] There were more than 5,500 Australian troops at its peak, including an infantry brigade, with armoured and aviation support.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Eventually 22 nations further contributed to the force which at its height had over 11,000 troops.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] The United States provided crucial logistic and diplomatic support throughout the crisis, while the cruiser USS Mobile Bay operated in open ocean at arm's length, whilst Australian, Canadian and British ships entered Dili.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] A US Marine infantry battalion of 1,000 men—plus organic armour and artillery—was also stationed off the coast aboard the USS *Belleau Wood* to provide a strategic reserve in the event of significant armed opposition.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] An estimated 1,400 civilians were killed both before and after the independence referendum.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Between 17 and 24 UNTAET personnel died during the mission.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Approximately 15 to 19 pro-Indonesian East Timorese militia members were killed in clashes with international forces.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] At least 15 UNAMET staff members were also killed during the crisis.
[src:french-navy/1999-east-timorese-crisis] Two East Timorese journalists affiliated with *Suara Timor Timur* and *Radio UNAMET*, were killed by militias amid the unrest.
[src:french-navy/2013-french-white-paper-on-defence-and-national-security] The **2013 French White Paper on Defense and National Security** is the most recent defence reform of the French Armed Forces and the fourth ever defence white paper in French history.
[src:french-navy/2013-french-white-paper-on-defence-and-national-security] The white paper reaffirmed France's commitment to NATO, the security of the European Union as well as its enhanced defence-relationship with the United Kingdom after the 2010 Lancaster House treaties on defence and security co-operation.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] The **Abkhazian Navy** is an operational-strategic formation of the Abkhazian Armed Forces, with its headquarters located in the vicinity of Sukhumi lighthouse.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] Its primary mission is to ensure the security of the self-proclaimed state of Abkhazia on the Black Sea coast.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] The Navy consists of littoral combat boats, a battalion of marines, parts of coastal troops and special forces.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] Joint exercises are often held with the Russian Navy.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] On December 23, 2014, the Parliament of Abkhazia ratified the **Treaty on Alliance and Strategic Partnership** with the Russian Federation.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] In accordance with the agreement, the main areas of cooperation are: conducting a coordinated foreign policy and common space of defense and security, promoting socio-economic development, and creating conditions for the full participation of Abkhazia in the post-Soviet era.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] Tensions had long existed between Abkhaz nationalists and ethnic Georgians under Soviet rule, leading to the 1989 Sukhumi riots.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] In the aftermath of the dissolution of the Soviet Union, Abkhazia remained as part of newly-independent Georgia.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] Tensions over autonomy demands led to the Abkhazian government proclaiming the independence of the region on 23 July 1992.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] On 14 August, Georgian police and National Guard units were dispatched to restore government control over Abkhazia, which marked the commencement of the war in Abkhazia.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] On 15 August, a marine tugboat was sent from Novorossiysk, Russia to Ochamchire to tow a decommissioned ship that had been sold to Turkey for scrap.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] As Georgian forces recaptured Ochamchire, the tug was seized and incorporated into the Georgian Navy.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] Two days later, a group organized by long-distance navigator Levan Katiba brought a number of vessels across the Gumista River.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] In Gudauta, the formation of a fleet was organized by Kuchkan Enik, who served from 29 August as head of the coast guard.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] By order of Colonel Sosnaliev, who was the Chief of Staff of the State Committee for Defense, Enik was given the right to appoint specialists and take sea boats throughout the Gudauta District.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] In September, Katiba began to form the Navy in the city of Pitsunda from floating seacraft, which at that time were in the hands of local Abkhaz militias.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] It originally consisted of 25 sailors, with Katiba being the first commander.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] Abkhaz sailors had a role in blocking the naval communications of the Georgian Armed Forces during the War in Abkhazia (1992–1993).
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] On 20 September 1993, a Tu-154 was shot down from a boat by a gunner of the Atar Battalion.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] The *Komsomolets of Abkhazia* and *Sukhum* carried out humanitarian transport to Sochi for Abkhaz refugees as part of a POW exchange program.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] On 12 November 1992, personnel of the Gudauta Coast Guard Base began to be deployed to the main naval base while transferring a boat and a Project 343ME Volga glider at the same time.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] On 19 December 1992, Katiba, began to address issues related to the replenishment of equipment, staffing of ships as well as ship documentation and launched a working group to address these needs for the young navy.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] The interim acting commander of the navy became Raul Nanba, who until then had served as midshipman in the Russian Navy.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] Raul Nanba resigned from his duties in January 1993.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] Captain Alexander Voinsky was appointed to this position, with Yuri Achba, a former commander of a nuclear submarine of the Soviet Navy's Northern Fleet, serving as chief of staff.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] In July of that year, Captain Ali Aliyev, a retired Dagestani graduate of the Caspian Higher Naval School in Baku.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] Further development of the navy was associated with the purchase of disarmed or decommissioned boats post-Soviet states. the countries of the former USSR.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] Until 2001, there were 9 fishing trawlers in the Sukhumi Naval Division.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] Between June and August 2004, the Navy of Abkhazia replenished four artillery boats from the 116th River Ship Brigade (located in Izmail) of the Black Sea Fleet, purchased with funds from the Abkhazian diaspora.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] In early September 2009, President Sergey Bagapsh ordered the navy "to destroy" Georgian Navy ships near the maritime border of Abkhazia.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] On 23 December 2014, the Parliament of Abkhazia ratified a treaty between Abkhazia and the Russian Federation, which laid the foundation for naval cooperation.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] As of October 5, 2023, Russia has signed a deal for a permanent naval base on the Abkhazian coast prompting criticism from Georgia.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] The Navy of Abkhazia is divided into three divisions, with the naval headquarters being located in the Sukhumi Lighthouse Area.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] The main fleet bases are located in Sukhumi, Ochamchire, Pitsunda.
[src:french-navy/abkhazian-navy] The number of sailors in the navy numbers more than 600 people.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] Vice-Admiral **Abraham Duquesne, marquis du Bouchet** (French pronunciation: [abʁa.am dykɛn]; c.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] 1610 – 2 February 1688) was a French naval officer, who also saw service as an admiral in the Swedish navy.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] He was born in Dieppe, a seaport, in 1610, and was a Huguenot.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] He was the son of a naval officer and therefore became a sailor himself, spending his early years in merchant service.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] Born into a Huguenot family in the early 17th century, he first went to sea under his father’s command, a ship’s captain.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] He served under King of France Louis XIII during the Thirty Years’ War and distinguished himself on several occasions, particularly in the battles of Tarragona and Cartagena, but was forced to leave the navy in 1644 after losing a ship.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] During the turbulent regency (the Fronde) of Louis XIV, the Sun King, he secured Cardinal Mazarin’s permission to serve in the Swedish Royal Navy alongside his brother.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] He fought in the Torstenson War between Sweden and Denmark and made his mark at the Battle of Fehmarn, capturing the flagship of the Danish commander Pros Mund.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] Returning to France, he rejoined the French Royal Navy and was sent in 1669 to relieve Candia, then under siege by the Turks.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] He took part in the Franco-Dutch War (1672–1678), fighting at the battles of Solebay (1672) and Stromboli (January 1676).
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] But it was at the battles of Augusta (April 1676) and Palermo that he truly stood out.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] He ended his career as a lieutenant general of the naval forces, his advancement hindered by his refusal to renounce his Protestant faith despite pressure from the Sun King and his advisors, including Colbert and Bossuet.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] In 1635, he became a *capitaine de vaisseau* (captain) in the French navy.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] He was appointed to the "Neptune" squadron in 1636.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] In May 1637, he gained some fame for capturing the island of Lerins from Spain.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] Around this time, his father died in a conflict with the Spanish, which permanently increased his animosity towards them and he sought revenge.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] He fought them viciously at the Battle of Guetaria in 1638, during the expedition to Corunna in 1639, and in the battles at Tarragona in 1641, Barcelona and the Cabo de Gata (also called in English battle of Cartagena).
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] Duquesne then left to join the Swedish Navy in 1643.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] He fought the Danish fleet personally commanded by King Christian IV at the Battle of Colberger Heide in the frigate *Regina* 34.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] Later, in the Battle of Fehmarn Belt, the Danes were decisively defeated, their admiral Pros Mund killed and his ship taken.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] After a peace had been reached between the Danes and the Swedes in 1645, he returned to France.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] He suppressed a revolt at Bordeaux (which was materially supported by his most hated foe, the Spanish) in 1650, during the Fronde outbreaks.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] During that same year, he created at his own expense a squadron with which he blockaded the Gironde, forcing that city to surrender.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] This earned him a promotion in rank to *chef d'escadre* (Rear-Admiral), a castle, and a gift of the entire isle of Indre, Loire-Atlantique.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] The French and the Spanish made peace in 1659, which left him to fight pirates in the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] In 1667 he was promoted '*Lieutenant-Général* (Vice-Admiral).
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] He fought the combined Dutch-Spanish fleet at the Battle of Stromboli and the Battle of Augusta where De Ruyter was mortally wounded.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] On 2 June he was present as second in command when the French fleet under Comte and Vivonne attacked and partly destroyed the combined Spanish-Dutch fleet at the Battle of Palermo, which secured French control of the Mediterranean.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] For this accomplishment he received a personal letter from Louis XIV and was given, in 1681, the title of marquis along with the estate of Bouchet, even though he was a Protestant.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] Duquesne also fought the Barbary pirates in 1681 and bombarded Algiers between 1682 and 1683.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] In response the Algerians tied the French consul Jean Le Vacher to their huge Baba Merzoug cannon and blasted him towards the French fleet in July 1683.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] Another French consul received the same treatment in 1688, and the cannon became known as La Consulaire.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] In that same year, 1684, he retired from poor health.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] He may have foreseen the revocation of the Edict of Nantes in 1685, though he was exempted from the proscription.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] Abraham's heart was placed in a silver box and sent to Aubonne, Switzerland after his death.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] More than a hundred years later in 1894 the box was discovered and moved to his birthplace in Dieppe.
[src:french-navy/abraham-duquesne] The Marquis Duquesne de Menneville, another famous mariner, was his grandnephew.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi is located on an island in the Persian Gulf, off the Central West Coast.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Most of the city and the Emirate reside on the mainland connected to the rest of the country.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] In 2023, Abu Dhabi's urban area had an estimated population of 2.5 million, out of 3.8 million in the emirate of Abu Dhabi.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The Abu Dhabi Investment Authority (ADIA), headquartered in the city, is estimated to manage approximately US$1 trillion in assets, making it the world's third-largest sovereign wealth fund after Norway's Government Pension Fund Global and China's CIC.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi has over a trillion US dollars' worth of assets under management in a combination of sovereign wealth funds headquartered there.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi houses local and federal government offices and is the home of the United Arab Emirates Government and the Supreme Council for Financial and Economic Affairs.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The city is home to the UAE's president, a member of the Al Nahyan family.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi's rapid development and urbanisation, coupled with the massive oil and gas reserves and production and relatively high average income, have transformed it into a large, developed metropolis.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] It is the country's centre of politics and industry, and a major culture and commerce centre.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi accounts for about two-thirds of the roughly $503 billion UAE economy.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The area surrounding Abu Dhabi abounds in archaeological evidence from historical civilisations, such as the Umm Al Nar Culture, which dates back to the third millennium BC.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Other settlements were also found farther outside the modern city of Abu Dhabi, including the eastern and western regions of the Emirate.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] On December 2, 1971, Abu Dhabi, along with five other emirates, formed the United Arab Emirates (UAE).
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] This union was marked by the establishment of a federal government and the appointment of Sheikh Zayed bin Sultan Al Nahyan as the first President of the UAE.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] "Abu" is Arabic for father, and "Dhabi" is the Arabic word for gazelle.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The Bani Yas, the tribe from which the Al Nahyan family are drawn, was originally settled in the Liwa Oasis in the Emirate's western region.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] This tribe was the most significant in the area, having over 20 subsections.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] In 1761, the discovery of fresh water by a hunting party led by Sheikh Dhiyab bin Isa Al Nahyan near the coast saw a settlement established there.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] A popular story is that the hunters were pursuing a gazelle, hence the name of the settlement.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The Al Bu Falah subsection of the tribe were the first to establish the new settlement and remained the source of the tribal rulers.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Originally consisting of a fort and twenty houses, within two years the town consisted of a settlement of some 400 houses.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The fort remains at the centre of Abu Dhabi today, the Qasr Al Hosn.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The pearl diving business was a key industry prior to the discovery of oil reserves.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] According to a source about pearling, the Persian Gulf was the best location for pearls.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The pearl industry boomed from the late 19th century through to the second decade of the 20th century, however it is believed to date back around 7,000 years.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Pearl divers dive for one to three minutes and would have dived as many as thirty times per day.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Air tanks and any other sort of mechanical device were forbidden.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The divers had a leather nose clip and leather coverings on their fingers and big toes to protect them while they searched for oysters.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The divers were not paid for a day's work but received a portion of the season's earnings.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] In the 19th century, as a result of treaties (known as "Truces" which gave the coast its name) entered into between Great Britain and the sheikhs of the Arab States of the Persian Gulf, Britain became the predominant influence in the area.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The main purpose of British interest was to protect the trade route to India from pirates, hence, the earlier name for the area, the "Pirate Coast".
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] After the suppression of piracy, other considerations came into play, such as a strategic need of the British to exclude other powers from the region.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Following their withdrawal from India in the year 1947, the British maintained their influence in Abu Dhabi as interest in the oil potential of the Persian Gulf grew.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] In the mid to late 1930s, as the pearl trade declined, interest grew in the oil possibilities of the region.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] On 5 January 1936, Petroleum Development Trucial Coast Ltd (PDTC), an associate company of the Iraq Petroleum Company, entered into a concession agreement with the ruler, Sheikh Shakhbut bin Sultan Al Nahyan, to explore for oil.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] This was followed by a seventy-five-year concession signed in January 1939.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Owing to the desert terrain, inland exploration was fraught with difficulties.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] In 1953, D'Arcy Exploration Company, the exploration arm of BP, obtained an offshore concession which was then transferred to a company created to operate the concession: Abu Dhabi Marine Areas (ADMA) was a joint venture between BP and Compagnie Française des Pétroles (later Total).
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] In 1958, using a marine drilling platform, the ADMA Enterprise, oil was discovered in the Umm Shaif field at a depth of about 2,669 metres (8,755 ft).
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] This was followed in 1959 by PDTC's onshore discovery well at Murban No.3.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] ADMA discovered the Bu Hasa oil field in 1962 and the Lower Zakum oil field in 1963.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Today, in addition to the oil fields mentioned, the main producing fields onshore are Asab, Sahil and Shah, and offshore are al-Bunduq, and Abu al-Bukhoosh.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Perceived mismanagement of the emirate's oil revenues, as well as fears of a pan-Arab uprising, led to the British backing a bloodless coup by Shakhbut's younger brother Zayed Al Nahyan on August 6, 1966.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The city of Abu Dhabi is on the southeastern side of the Arabian Peninsula, adjoining the Persian Gulf.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] It is on an island less than 250 metres (820 ft) from the mainland and is joined to the mainland by the Maqta and Mussafah Bridges.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] A third, Sheikh Zayed Bridge, designed by Zaha Hadid, opened in late 2010.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi Island is also connected to Saadiyat Island by a five-lane motorway bridge.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Al-Mafraq bridge connects the city to Reem Island and was completed in early 2011.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] This is a multi-layer interchange bridge and it has 27 lanes which allow roughly 25,000 automobiles to move per hour.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] There are three major bridges in the project, the largest has eight lanes, four leaving Abu Dhabi city and four coming in.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Most of Abu Dhabi city is located on the island itself, but it has many suburban districts on the mainland, for example, Khalifa City A, B, and C; Khalifa City Al Raha Beach; Al Bahia City A, B, and C; Al Shahama; Al Rahba; Between Two Bridges; Baniyas; Shamkha; Al Wathba and Mussafah Residential.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Gulf waters of Abu Dhabi holds the world's largest population of Indo-Pacific humpbacked dolphins.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] To the east of the island is the Mangrove National Park, located on Al Qurm Corniche.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] *Al-Qurm* (ٱلْقُرْم) is Arabic for "The Mangrove".
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi has a hot desert climate (Köppen climate classification *BWh*).
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Sunny blue skies can be expected throughout the year.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The months of May to September are generally extremely hot and humid.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The peak summer months are July and August, with maximum temperatures averaging above 40 °C (104 °F).
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] During this time, sandstorms occur intermittently, in some cases reducing visibility to a few metres.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Due to high humidity, especially in coastal areas, the heat index, or "feels-like" temperature, can be significantly higher than the actual air temperature.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Dust storms are common during the hot, dry months, affecting air quality and visibility.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The cooler season is from November to March, which ranges between moderately hot to mild.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] This period also sees dense fog on some days and a few days of rain.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] On average, January is the coolest month of the year.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Since the Tropic of Cancer passes through the emirate, the southern part falls within the Tropics.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Despite the coolest month having an 18.8 °C (65.8 °F) average, its climate is far too dry to be classed as tropical.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi City is the capital of the Emirate of Abu Dhabi, and the local government of Abu Dhabi is directly led by the Ruler of Abu Dhabi.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi is the largest, and wealthiest of the seven emirates, and it plays a crucial role in the UAE's governance and economy.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The Ruler has the executive authority to issue local laws, create or merge government departments, and appoint heads of departments.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The Ruler of Abu Dhabi appoints the Abu Dhabi Executive Council to lead the day-to-day management of government affairs.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The Department of Municipal Affairs is responsible for municipal affairs for the entire emirate.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi is part of the Central Capital District, which is separate from the eastern and western municipal regions of the Emirate of Abu Dhabi.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The main settlement of the eastern region, officially "Al Ain Region" since a decree by Sheikh Khalifa in March 2017, is Al Ain City, and that of the western region, officially "Al Dhafra Region" as per the same decree, is Madinat Zayed.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The Government of the Emirate of Abu Dhabi officially leads both the city and greater emirate with agencies operating out of Abu Dhabi with branches in other cities.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The Abu Dhabi Government has agencies and organisations operating across the emirate such as the Abu Dhabi Urban Planning Council and the Regulation and Supervision Bureau, which are responsible for infrastructure projects in the city.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Because Abu Dhabi is the capital of the UAE, it also serves as the headquarters of the Federal government of the United Arab Emirates, the office of the President of the United Arab Emirates, and seat of the Federal Supreme Council.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The Abu Dhabi Government Media Office (ADGMO) was formed in 2019 and is responsible for representing the government in the media, organising press conferences for the emirate and monitoring local and international media.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] It is a state-sponsored organisation that communicates the latest developments in the capital, and the emirate's vision, values and traditions.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The city was planned under the guidance of Sheikh Zayed by Japanese architect Katsuhiko Takahashi in 1967 initially for a population of 40,000.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The density of Abu Dhabi varies, with high employment density in the central area, high residential densities in central downtown and lower densities in the suburban districts.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] In the dense areas, most of the concentration is achieved with medium- and high-rise buildings.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Other notable modern buildings include the Aldar Headquarters, the first circular skyscraper in the Middle East and the Emirates Palace with its design inspired by Arab heritage.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi already has a number of supertall skyscrapers under construction throughout the city.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Some of the tallest buildings on the skyline include the 382 m (1,253.28 ft) Central Market Residential Tower, the 324 m (1,062.99 ft) The Landmark and the 74-story, 310 m (1,017.06 ft) Sky Tower, all of them completed.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Many other skyscrapers over 150 m (492.13 ft) (500 ft) are either proposed or approved and could transform the city's skyline.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] As of July 2008, there were 62 high-rise buildings 23 to 150 m (75.46 to 492.13 ft) under construction, approved for construction, or proposed for construction.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The Sheikh Zayed Grand Mosque represents a key fixture of the city's architectural patrimony.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Its construction was initiated under the administration of the late President Sheikh Zayed bin Sultan Al Nahyan, a key figure in the foundation of the modern United Arab Emirates.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The mosque was constructed with materials from countries around the world, including Italy, Germany, Morocco, Pakistan, India, Turkey, Iran, China, the United Kingdom, New Zealand, Greece, and the United Arab Emirates.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] More than 3,000 workers and 38 contracting companies took part in the construction of the mosque.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Consideration of durability motivated the choice of many materials specified in the design of the structure.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] These materials include marble, stone, gold, semi-precious stones, crystals, and ceramics.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The building is large enough to safely contain a maximum of approximately 41,000 people.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The overall structure is 22,412 square metres (241,240 square feet).
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The internal prayer halls were initially opened in December 2007.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] As one of the most visited buildings in the UAE, the Sheikh Zayed Grand Mosque Center was established to manage the day-to-day operations, as a place of worship and Friday gathering and as a centre of learning and discovery through its education and visitor programs.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] In July 2019, the Grand Mosque was listed among the top global attractions by TripAdvisor.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] As a part of its Travelers Choice Awards, the travel website placed the architectural masterpiece on number three out of the 750 landmarks considered from 68 countries.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] In May 2021, the Sheikh Zayed Grand Mosque Center attended the Arabian Travel Market 2021 exhibition.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] This was part of the centre's core strategy to be active in the religious and cultural aspects of society.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The Founder's Memorial, a monument and visitor centre in Abu Dhabi, United Arab Emirates (UAE) is a memorial to Sheikh Zayed bin Sultan Al Nahyan, the first President of the United Arab Emirates, who died in 2004.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The memorial consists of an open Heritage Garden and Sanctuary Garden at the centre of which is a cubic pavilion housing The Constellation, an artwork dedicated to Zayed's memory.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The UAE Presidential Palace, *Qaṣr Al-Waṭan* ("Palace of the Nation"), opened to the public in March 2019.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] It was built on the grounds of Ladies beach and construction was finished in 2018.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Historically, 'barza' refers to a majlis session during which important matters can be brought to the attention of a Sheikh.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] After the Great Hall, it is the largest space in the UAE's Presidential Palace which holds up to 300 guests.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The Abrahamic Family House, a multi-faith complex on Saadiyat Island, includes the Imam Al-Tayeb Mosque, St.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Francis Church, and the Moses Ben Maimon Synagogue, the UAE's first purpose-built synagogue.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The project was inaugurated on 16 February 2023 and officially opened to the public on 1 March 2023.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] On 22 September 2019, the Department of Community Development (DCD) in Abu Dhabi held a ceremony to grant licenses to 17 churches and the first-ever traditional Hindu temple.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The listed churches were Catholic, Orthodox and Protestant churches, including St Joseph's Cathedral.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The initiative was taken under the slogan "A Call for Harmony", to allow people from all religions and cultures to practice their faith in the country.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Qasr Al Hosn is the oldest building in the Emirate of Abu Dhabi, built by the Bani Yas tribe in 1761.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] It was once the seat of the government and the palace of the ruling Al Nahyan family.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Today, it is a museum open to all visitors portraying the history of Abu Dhabi and early lifestyles.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] It is where the visitors will notice the art Talli, a traditional form of decorative embroidery done by women, and the making of Al Sadu patterns which represent symbols of daily life.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] A three-screen mini-theatre is available which describes the traditional form of weaving practised by Bedouin women.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi has several parks, gardens, a zoo, and more than 400 kilometres (249 miles) of coastline, of which 10 kilometres (6 miles) are public beaches.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The UAE's large hydrocarbon wealth gives it one of the highest GDP per capita in the world and Abu Dhabi owns the majority of these resources 95% of the oil and 92% of gas.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi thus holds 9% of the world's proven oil reserves (98.2bn barrels) and almost 5% of the world's natural gas (5.8 billion cubic metres or 200 billion cubic feet).
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] As of April 2022, oil production in the UAE was about 3.0 million barrels per day (BPD).
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The UAE is looking to expand its maximum production capacity from approximately 4 million BPD to 5 million BPD by 2030.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] In recent years, the focus has turned to gas as increasing domestic consumption for power, desalination and reinjection of gas into oil fields increases demand.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Gas extraction is not without its difficulties, however, as demonstrated by the sour gas project at Shah where the gas is rich in hydrogen sulfide content and expensive to develop and process.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] In 2009, the government diversified its economic plans.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Served by high oil prices, the country's non-oil and gas GDP outstripped that attributable to the energy sector.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Non-oil and gas GDP now constitutes 64% of the UAE's total GDP.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] This trend is reflected in Abu Dhabi with substantial new investment in industry, real estate, tourism and retail.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] As Abu Dhabi is the largest oil producer of the UAE, it has reaped the most benefits from this trend.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] It has taken on an active diversification and liberalisation program to reduce the UAE's reliance on the hydrocarbon sector.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] This is evident in the emphasis on industrial diversification with the completion of free zones, Industrial City of Abu Dhabi, twofour54 Abu Dhabi media free zone and the construction of another, ICAD II, in the pipeline.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] There has also been a drive to promote tourism and real estate with the Abu Dhabi Tourism Authority and the Tourism and Development Investment Company undertaking several large-scale development projects.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] These will be served by improved transport infrastructure, with a new port, an expanded airport and a proposed rail link between Abu Dhabi and Dubai all in the development stages.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi's Emirate is the wealthiest of the UAE in terms of Gross domestic product (GDP) and per capita income.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] More than $1 trillion is invested worldwide in the city.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] In 2010, the GDP per capita reached $49,600, which ranks ninth in the world.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Taxation in Abu Dhabi, as in the rest of the UAE, is nil for a resident or a non-bank, non-oil company.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi is also planning many future projects sharing with the Cooperation Council for the Arab States of the Gulf (GCC) and taking 29% of all the GCC future plannings.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The UAE has a fast-growing economy: in 2006 the per capita income grew by 9%, providing a GDP per capita of $49,700 and ranking third in the world at purchasing power parity.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi's government is looking to expand revenue from oil and gas production to tourism and other things that would attract different types of people.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] This goal is seen in the amount of attention Abu Dhabi is giving its International Airport.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The airport experienced a 30%+ growth in passenger usage in 2009.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] This idea of diversifying the economy is also seen in the Abu Dhabi Economic Vision 2030 planned by the Abu Dhabi Urban Planning Council.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] In this plan, Abu Dhabi's economy will be sustainable and not dependent on any single source of revenue.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] More specifically the non-oil portion of income is planned to be increased from about 40% to about 70%.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] As of July 2019, Abu Dhabi allocated $163 million to finance global entertainment partners as part of its plan to diversify the economy and wean it off oil.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Many Hollywood and other national film production teams have used parts of the UAE as filming locations.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Neighbouring Dubai gets a lot of attention, but in recent years Abu Dhabi has become a popular destination.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The Etihad Towers and Emirates Palace Hotel were some of the city's landmarks used as filming locations for the movie *Furious 7*, in which cars rush through the building and smashed through the windows of the towers.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] In 2018, Abu Dhabi launched Ghadan 21, a string of initiatives to diversify the economy.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] There are four main areas these initiatives must fall under: business and investment, society, knowledge and innovation, and lifestyle.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The first phase includes over 50 initiatives that reflect the priorities of citizens, residents and investors.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The desalinated water supply and power production are managed by the Abu Dhabi Water and Electricity Authority (ADWEA).
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] As of 2006, it supplied 560.2 MiGD (million imperial gallons per day) of water, while the water demand for 2005–06 was estimated to be 511 MiGD.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The Environment Agency of Abu Dhabi (EAD) states that groundwater is the most significant source of water, as well as desalinated potable water, and treated sewage effluent.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] At 40.6 MiGD, the Umm Al Nar storage is the largest water source for Abu Dhabi, followed by the rivers Shuweihat and Taweelah.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] With falling groundwater level and rising population density, Abu Dhabi faces a severely acute water shortage.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] On average each Abu Dhabi resident uses 550 litres (120 imp gal; 150 US gal) of water per day.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi daily produces 1,532 tonnes of solid wastes which are dumped at three landfill sites by the Abu Dhabi Municipality.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The daily domestic wastewater production is 330 MiGD and industrial waste water is 40 MiGD.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] A large portion of the sewerage flows as waste into streams and separation plants.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The city's per capita electricity consumption is about 41,000 kWh and the total supplied is 8,367 MW as of 2007.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The distribution of electricity is carried out by companies run by SCIPCO Power and APC Energy.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] As part of UAE's Energy Strategy 2050 to reduce the carbon emission of power generation by 70%, Noor Abu Dhabi solar park project which is the largest solar project in the world was completed on 2 July 2019.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The Abu Dhabi Fire Service runs 13 fire stations that attend about 2,000 fire and rescue calls per year.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] State-owned Etisalat and private du communication companies provide telephone and cell phone service to the city.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Cellular coverage is extensive, and both GSM and CDMA (from Etisalat and Du) services are available.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Etisalat, the government-owned telecommunications provider, held a virtual monopoly over telecommunication services in Abu Dhabi prior to the establishment of other, smaller telecommunications companies such as Emirates Integrated Telecommunications Company (EITC – better known as Du) in 2006.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The Internet was introduced into Abu Dhabi in 1995.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The current network is supported by a bandwidth of 6 GB, with 50,000 dialup and 150,000 broadband ports.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Etisalat announced implementing a fiber-to-the-home (FTTH) network in Abu Dhabi during the third quarter of 2009 to make the emirate the world's first city to have such a network.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi in the 1960s and 70s was planned for a predicted topmost population of 600,000.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Following the urban planning ideals of the time period, the city has high-density tower blocks and wide grid-pattern roads.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The population density is at its apex on the most northerly part of the island.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] At this point, the main streets have a large amount of 20- to 30-story towers.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] These towers are in a rectangular pattern, and inside is an ordinary grid pattern of roads with low rise buildings such as 2-story villas or 6-story low-rise buildings.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Due to this planning, a modern city with tall offices, apartment buildings, broad boulevards, and busy shops is present.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Principal thoroughfares are the Corniche, Airport Road, Sheikh Zayed Street, Hamdan Street, and Khalifa Street.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi is known in the region for its greenery; the former desert strip today includes numerous parks and gardens.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The design of the inner city roads and main roads are quite organised.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Starting from the Corniche, all horizontal streets are oddly numbered, while all vertical streets are evenly numbered.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Mail is generally delivered to post-office boxes only; however, there is door-to-door delivery for commercial organisations.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] There are many parks throughout the city.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Entrance is usually free for children, however, there is often an entrance fee for adults.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The Corniche, the city's seaside promenade, is about 10 kilometres (6.2 mi) in length, with gardens, playgrounds, and a BMX/skateboard ring.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] In 2007, the Abu Dhabi Urban Planning Council (UPC) was established, which is the agency responsible for the future of Abu Dhabi's urban environments and the expert authority behind the visionary Plan Abu Dhabi 2030 Urban Structure Framework Plan that was published in September 2007.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The UPC is also working on similar plans for the regions of Al-Ain and Al-Gharbia.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Human rights organisations have heavily criticised violations of human rights in Abu Dhabi.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] As with other parts of the UAE, foreign workers are not given proper treatment and many companies (both government and private) have yet to improve working conditions.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] In 2025, Abu Dhabi was ranked as the safest city in the world for the ninth year running by the statistical analysis website Numbeo.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi ranks as the 67th most expensive city in the world and the second-most in the region behind Dubai.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] As of 2014, 477,000 of 2,650,000 people living in the emirate were UAE nationals.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Approximately 80% of the population were expatriates.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The median age in the emirate was about 30.1 years.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The crude birth rate, as of 2005, was 13.6%, while the crude death rate was about 2%.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Article 7 of the UAE's Provisional Constitution declares Islam the official state religion of the UAE.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The majority of the inhabitants of Abu Dhabi are migrants from Nepal, India, Pakistan, Russia, Ethiopia, Somalia, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, the Philippines, China, Uganda, Vietnam, the United Kingdom, France, Italy, Tanzania and various countries from across the Arab world.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Some of these expatriates have been in the country for decades with only a few of them awarded citizenship.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Consequently, English, Hindi-Urdu (Hindustani), Malayalam, Tamil, Telugu, Gujarati, Marathi, Tulu, Somali, Tigrinya, Amharic and Bengali are widely spoken.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The native-born population are Arabic-speaking Arabs who are part of a clan-based society.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The Al Nahyan family, part of the al-Falah branch of the Bani Yas clan, rules the emirate and has a central place in society.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] There are also Arabs who are from other parts of the Arab world.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Rapidly developing transportation in Abu Dhabi city is anchored by vast systems of highways connecting various islands and suburbs together alongside expanding public and private transport options.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The main Abu Dhabi island is connected by three vast highways with their own bridges, the oldest of which is Al Maqta Bridge, built in 1968 as the first connection to the previously small fishing village on the island, now part of the E22 highway.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] As the city expands, new bridges and roads have been constructed, or are currently under construction to link the main island with Al Maryah Island, Al Reem Island, Saadiyat Island, and other previously undeveloped islands.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] For example, in 2023, Sheikh Khaled bin Mohamed Al Nahyan inaugurated the Umm Yifeenah Bridge, an 11 km highway connection between Al Reem Island and Sheikh Zayed bin Sultan Street.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] This change, and many other, are a part of Abu Dhabi's 2030 Urban Structure Framework Plan.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Zayed International Airport (AUH) is the city's main aviation hub and the second busiest airport in the UAE.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Passenger numbers at Zayed International Airport rose by 17.2 percent in 2015, with more than 23 million travelers passing through its terminals during that year.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] A second runway and new terminal was also built recently.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] In July 2024, it was reported that the airport launched the world's first-of-its-kind "Smart Travel" biometric.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] On 30 June 2019, the Department of Community Development (DCD) in Abu Dhabi officially inaugurated a multi-faith prayer room at Zayed International Airport.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Located away from the main airport, the prayer room aims at enhancing the country's "position as an international hub for tolerance".
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi City is additionally served by the Al Bateen Executive Airport, situated on the main Abu Dhabi island, which was the old international airport for Abu Dhabi until AUH opened in 1982.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The airport underwent renovation and expansion in 2022 to accommodate twin-aisle jets and resumed operation to private, business, and VIP traffic in addition to hosting an Abu Dhabi Police search and rescue base.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] On December 5, 2024, Zayed International Airport in Abu Dhabi (AUH) won the title of "World's Most Beautiful Airport" at the Prix Versailles, a prestigious award for architecture and design.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The award recognised its impressive architectural design in the Airports category.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi City is connected to the second phase of the Etihad Rail network, completed in 2023, for freight operations across the seven emirates.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Passenger traffic has been confirmed and will allow for travel from Abu Dhabi city to other emirates on the network, however no date on commencement of operation has been set.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Public transport systems in Abu Dhabi include public buses, taxis, ferries, and hydroplanes.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] A massive expansion of public transport is anticipated within the framework of the government's Surface Transport Master Plan 2030.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The expansion was expected to see 130 km (81 mi) of metro and 340 km (210 mi) of tramways and bus rapid transit (BRT) routes.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The city has nonetheless planned for further smart public transport options in various areas within the city, such as Yas Island and Saadiyat Island, in addition to expected rail service to other nearby cities.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The first town bus entered service in about 1969 but this was all part of a very informal service.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] There are other inter-city buses departing the Abu Dhabi central bus station; these inter-city buses are not only intra-emirate buses, but also inter-emirate services.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] On 30 June 2008, the Department of Transport began public bus service in Abu Dhabi with four routes.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] There are also public buses serving the airport.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] In an attempt to entice people to use the bus system, all routes were zero-fare until the end of 2008.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The four routes, which operate between 6 am and midnight every day, run at a frequency of 10 to 20 minutes.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Within the first week of service, the bus network had seen high usage.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Some of the buses, which have a maximum capacity of 45 passengers, only had room for standing left.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Some bus drivers reported as many as 100 passengers on a bus at one time.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Due to the new, zero-fare bus service success, many taxi drivers were losing business.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Taxi drivers have seen a considerable decrease in the demand for taxis while lines were forming for the buses.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] As of 2021, the Abu Dhabi public bus system had completed 53.3 million passenger trips, with a fleet of 583 buses for the city of Abu Dhabi.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] In 2022, Abu Dhabi launched autonomous self-driving public transport options in Yas Island and Saadiyat Island.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The route in Saadiyat Island stops at cultural and tourist stops such as Louvre Abu Dhabi, NYU Abu Dhabi, and Sorbonne University Abu Dhabi whereas the Yas Island route focuses on the attractions in the island such as Ferrari World Abu Dhabi.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The expansion include autonomous trams (Automated Rapid Transit or "ART"), taxis, and minibuses.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] During October 2023, the Integrated Transport Centre (ITC) launched the ART Service on mainland Abu Dhabi as a pilot phase as part of the Smart Mobility project.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] It spans approximately 27 kilometres from Reem Mall, Al Reem Island, until Marina Mall, serving 25 stations in total.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] In 2025, WeRide and Uber announced the launch of Level 4 fully driverless Robotaxi commercial operations.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Public commercial operations commenced on 26 November without a vehicle specialist inside the AV, starting with Yas Island.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] This initiative is supported by Abu Dhabi's Integrated Transport Centre.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The others are Musaffah Port and Khalifa Port, which opened in 2012.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] They are owned by Abu Dhabi Ports Company and managed by Abu Dhabi Terminals.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Water transport includes water taxis which can accommodate up to 12 passengers, and ferries which can carry up to 100 passengers on board.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Water taxis can be hired for point-to-point travel across the city's waterways, offering a convenient option for shorter trips, and ferry transport system is a convenient and scenic way to travel between the city's islands and mainland.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] In 2021, the number of passengers who used public ferries reached 114,093.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi introduced four toll gates in 2021 on all bridges (Sheikh Zayed Bridge, Maqtaa Bridge, Mussafah Bridge, and Sheikh Khalifa Bridge) entering the main Abu Dhabi island that only operate during peak hours, and by year-end had over 1.8 million registered cars in the system.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Drivers must manually create an account to add balance to their toll gate allowance.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi's toll gate system, known as **Darb**, is aimed at reducing traffic congestion and promoting smoother traffic flow.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Drivers must register their vehicles on the **Darb app** or the official website.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The system automatically deducts the toll charges from a prepaid account.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi's first flying taxi vertiport will open at the Zayed Port Cruise Terminal by late 2025.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] It will serve helicopters and eVTOLs, offering direct access to Saadiyat Island, the Corniche, and the Louvre Abu Dhabi.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi has a diverse and multicultural society.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The city's cultural imprint as a small, ethnically homogeneous pearling community was changed with the arrival of other ethnic groups and nationals—first by the Iranians in the early 1900s, and later by various African, Asian, European, and Middle Eastern ethnicities in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi has been criticised for perpetuating a class-based society, where migrant workers are in the lower classes, and suffer abuse which "is endemic to the system".
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Major holidays in Abu Dhabi include *Eid al Fitr* which marks the end of *Ramadan*, Eid ul-Adha which marks the end of Hajj, and National Day (2 December) which marks the formation of the United Arab Emirates.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] This unique socioeconomic development in the Persian Gulf has meant that Abu Dhabi is generally more tolerant than its neighbours, including Saudi Arabia.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Emiratis have been known for their tolerance; Christian churches, Hindu temples, Sikh gurdwaras (with the first synagogue commencing construction in 2020), and Buddhist temples can be found alongside mosques.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The cosmopolitan atmosphere is gradually growing; as a result, there are a variety of African, Asian, European, Middle Eastern, and Western schools, cultural centres, and themed restaurants.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi is home to several cultural institutions, including the Cultural Foundation and the National Theater.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The Cultural Foundation, while closed for reconstruction as of spring 2011, is home to the UAE Public Library and Cultural Center.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Various cultural societies such as the Abu Dhabi Classical Music Society have a strong and visible following in the city.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The recently launched Emirates Foundation offers grants in support of the arts and to advance science and technology, education, environmental protection, and social development.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The International Prize for Arabic Fiction (IPAF) will be based in Abu Dhabi.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The city also stages hundreds of conferences and exhibitions each year in its state-of-the-art venues, including the Abu Dhabi National Exhibition Centre (ADNEC), which is the Persian Gulf's largest exhibition centre and welcomes around 1.8 million visitors every year.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The Red Bull Air Race World Series has been a spectacular sporting staple for the city for many years, bringing tens of thousands to the waterfront.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Another major event is the Abu Dhabi International Petroleum Exhibition and Conference (ADIPEC).
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The diversity of cuisine in Abu Dhabi reflects the cosmopolitan nature of society.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Arab food is trendy and is available everywhere in the city, from the small shawarma to the upscale restaurants in the city's many hotels.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Fast food and South Asian cuisine are also trendy and are widely available.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The sale and consumption of pork, though not illegal, is regulated and sold only to non-Muslims in designated areas.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Similarly, the sale of alcoholic beverages is regulated.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] A liquor permit is required to purchase alcohol; however, alcohol is available in bars and restaurants within four or five stars hotels.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] *Shisha* and *qahwa* boutiques are also popular in Abu Dhabi.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Poetry in Abu Dhabi and the UAE is highly regarded and often centres around satire, religion, family, chivalry, and love.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] According to an article from an Abu Dhabi tourism page, sheikhs, teachers, sailors, and princes make up a large bulk of the poets within the UAE. al-Khalil ibn Ahmad al-Farahidi formed a unique form of poetry to the UAE in the 8th century and was written in 16 metre.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Another Emirati poet, Ibn Daher, is from the 17th century.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Daher is important because he used Nabati poetry (AKA Bedouin poetry), a type of poetry written in the vernacular instead of classical/religious Arabic.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Other important poets from the UAE are Mubarak Al Oqaili (1880–1954), Salem bin Ali al Owais (1887–1959), and Abdulla bin Sulayem (1905–1976).
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] These poets made headway in Classical Arabic poetry as opposed to the Nabati poetry of the 17th century.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Today in Abu Dhabi, a group called the Abu Dhabi Cultural Foundation works to preserve the art and culture of the city.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] According to an article from the English Pen Atlas, Al Jawaher wal la'li was the first manuscript to come out of the UAE.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] According to another article, this book was written in the 1990s and was banned in the city for some time for making accusations about the ruling family.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] For cultural influences, Abu Dhabi, since 2010, has become one of the major shooting spots for many film companies, including Hollywood.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] In 2024, the Madison Square Garden Company confirmed that a second Sphere venue, identical to the Sphere in Las Vegas would be built in Abu Dhabi.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The following year in 2025 it was confirmed that Disney would build a theme-park in Abu Dhabi called Disneyland Abu Dhabi.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Abu Dhabi is home to international and local private schools and universities, including government-sponsored INSEAD, New York University Abu Dhabi, Khalifa University, Higher Colleges of Technology, Sorbonne University Abu Dhabi, and Abu Dhabi University.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] New York University opened a government-sponsored satellite campus in Abu Dhabi in September 2010.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] All schools in the emirate are under the authority of the Abu Dhabi Education Council.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] This organisation oversees and administers public schools and licenses and inspects private schools.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] From 2009, the council has brought over thousands of licensed teachers from native English speaking countries to support their New School Model Program in government schools.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Every year in the season of admissions, an exhibition is launched in Abu Dhabi Exhibition Center under government supervision.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Universities from every corner of the world exhibit their career programs and scholarship programs.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] Heriot-Watt University, University of Bolton, Cambridge University, Oxford University, the Petroleum Institute, Khalifa University, and Abu Dhabi University attend.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] In October 2019, Abu Dhabi announced the world's first graduate-level AI research institution, Mohamed bin Zayed University of Artificial Intelligence (MBZUAI).
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] It enables graduation for students, businesses and governments to advance artificial intelligence.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p01] The university began accepting applications for masters and PhD programmes a year before the classes, which are scheduled to begin in September 2020.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] Abu Dhabi has a diverse and expanding sporting culture underpinned by investments in sporting infrastructure and the hosting of global sporting events.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] Liwa Motorsport and traditional sports such as camel racing and equestrian sports have developed alongside popular modern sports such as Jiu-jitsu and football.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] Abu Dhabi follows the UAE's National Sport Strategy 2031 which aims to increase general participation in sports and expand the types and frequency of sport facilities available in the city.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] Zayed Sport City (ZSC) is a large free zone complex in the heart of Abu Dhabi city with a mixed-use of properties and sporting facilities to encourage sport participation.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] ZSC offers practice facilities for basketball, billiards, football, paintball, and a dedicated ice rink.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] The complex is also home to the Zayed Sports City Stadium, the largest in the UAE with a seating capacity of 45,000 and is the headquarters of the Abu Dhabi Sports Council, which is responsible for hosting events in the city and Mubadala Arena, the home of the UAE Jiu Jitsu team.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] Jiu Jitsu is a popular sport in the city with a dedicated complex in the Mubadala Arena.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] It is a 'Soft Art' originated from the ancient martial art of the Samurai in Japan several centuries ago and it has been adopted by Brazil in the early 1900s.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] Jiu Jitsu does not include punches or kicks, but it applies the techniques such as throws, control positions and locks.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] Abu Dhabi government's Abu Dhabi Education Council (ADEC) maintains a comprehensive after-school program for interested and talented jiujitsu students.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] The Abu Dhabi Jiujitsu Schools Program began in 2008 under the patronage of crown prince (now President) Mohammed bin Zayed Al Nahyan, a keen Brazilian jiu-jitsu competitor.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] The program launched in 14 schools for pupils in grades 6 and 7 and has since expanded to 42 government schools, with 81 Brazilian coaches brought in as instructors.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] 9 to 13-year-old students are taught Brazilian jiu-jitsu as part of the curriculum.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] The plan is for up to 500 schools to be participating in the school-Jitsu program by 2015.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] The project was set up by special request of Sheikh Mohammad bin Zayed Al Nahyan to the head coach of the Emirates jiu-jitsu team, Carlos "Carlão" Santos, now also the managing director of the School-Jitsu Project.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] Football is the most popular sport in the city and the city has four football stadiums, namely Al Jazeera Stadium, Al Wahda Stadium, Sheikh Zayed Football Stadium (Zayed Sports City) and Hazza Stadium.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] The city hosts the Al Jazira Club, Al Wahda FC, and Baniyas Club, all of which compete at the UAE Pro League.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] In addition to local tournaments, the city has hosted international football events including five FIFA Club World Cup and the 2019 AFC Asian Cup.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] The city hosts the Abu Dhabi Grand Prix of Formula One, which has been held at the Yas Marina Circuit since 2009.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] The race takes place late in the Formula One season in November or December, and it is usually the last race of the season.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] The Yas Marina Circuit is one of the most expensive racing tracks built and regularly hosts various other local races and tours.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] The circuit has also hosted other events such as the V8 Supercars series of Dubai.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] Abu Dhabi regularly hosts the International Judo Federation Abu Dhabi grand slam.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] Engendering some criticism, the International Judo Federation refused to allow the Israeli flag and the Israeli national anthem at the international games in 2017.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] Some referred to this action as anti-Semitic.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] The ban on Israeli symbols was lifted in 2018 and Israeli flag and the national anthem was allowed to be displayed.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] Israeli minister of sports Miri Regev was also allowed to attend the event.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] In March 2019, Abu Dhabi hosted the first Special Olympics World Games in the Middle East.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] The event took place from 14 to 21 March 2019 and featured more than 7,500 athletes participating in 24 sporting disciplines.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] The official World Games Flame of Hope was lit in Athens and flown to Abu Dhabi, where it then embarked on the torch run, visiting all seven emirates of the UAE.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] It was the first time the Special Olympics World Games were hosted in the Middle East and North Africa region, with Abu Dhabi being the host city.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] More than 2,500 coaches and 20,000+ volunteers were available in the Olympics.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] The city has hosted multiple international cricket tournaments, such as the ICC Men's T20 World Cup, and tennis events such as the Mubadala World Tennis Championship.It has also hosted many UFC events.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] World Abu Dhabi, SeaWorld Abu Dhabi and Jubail Mangrove Park.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] On 29 April 2022, Abu Dhabi announced a 100% capacity for commercial activities, tourist attractions and events in the emirate.
[src:french-navy/abu-dhabi-p02] The Walt Disney Company announced on 7 May 2025 that it plans to build its seventh worldwide theme park resort in Abu Dhabi on Yas Island.
[src:french-navy/admiral-of-france] The title was created in 1270 by Louis IX of France, during the Eighth Crusade.
[src:french-navy/admiral-of-france] At the time, it was equivalent to the office of Constable of France.
[src:french-navy/admiral-of-france] The Admiral was responsible for defending the coasts of Picardy, Normandy, Aunis, and Saintonge.
[src:french-navy/admiral-of-france] In times of war, it was his responsibility to assemble French merchant ships into a navy.
[src:french-navy/admiral-of-france] He had to arm, equip, and supply the ships for the course of the war, and give letters of marque to corsairs.
[src:french-navy/admiral-of-france] In peacetime, he was responsible for the maintenance of the royal fleet (when one existed).
[src:french-navy/admiral-of-france] He was also responsible for maritime commerce and the merchant fleet.
[src:french-navy/admiral-of-france] During the modern era, few admirals were sailors; moreover, with the exception of Claude d'Annebault, none of them actually commanded the fleet.
[src:french-navy/admiral-of-france] The title, like the title of Constable, had much more political importance (which would eventually lead to the suppression of both titles).
[src:french-navy/admiral-of-france] It was also a lucrative position: the admiral was allocated a part of the fines and confiscations imposed by the admiralty, and he had a right to unclaimed ships and shipwrecks as well as a tenth of the spoils taken in battle.
[src:french-navy/admiral-of-france] He also had juridical rights, comparable to those exercised by the constable and the marshal.
[src:french-navy/admiral-of-france] This was known as the *Table de marbre*, after the seat of the admiralty in Paris.
[src:french-navy/admiral-of-france] A second headquarters of the admiralty was established at Rouen, and about 50 other headquarters were set up at various other places around the coast of France.
[src:french-navy/admiral-of-france] These tribunals judged cases dealing with fishing disputes and any crimes committed in the country's ports.
[src:french-navy/admiral-of-france] The Admiralty was suppressed in 1627 by Cardinal Richelieu, who had been named to the newly created post of Grand Master of Navigation and who wanted to bring all naval authority under one position.
[src:french-navy/admiral-of-france] The position was recreated in 1669, but was now only an honorific title.
[src:french-navy/admiral-of-france] The first new admiral was Louis, Count of Vermandois, who at the time was only 2 years old.
[src:french-navy/admiral-of-france] Thereafter, only Louis Alexandre, Count of Toulouse involved himself in maritime affairs.
[src:french-navy/admiral-of-france] It was suppressed once more in 1791, restored in 1805 in the person of Marshal of France Joachim Murat.
[src:french-navy/admiral-of-france] Currently, the most recent Admiral of France was François Thomas Tréhouart, in 1869.
[src:french-navy/admiral-of-france] Henry VI of England appointed two English aristocrats during the ministrations of Louis de Culant and André de Laval-Montmorency.
[src:french-navy/admiral-of-france] Accordingly, they were not recognized by the Kingdom of France.
[src:french-navy/admiral] The word *admiral* in Middle English comes from Anglo-French *amiral*, "commander", from Medieval Latin *admiralis*, *admirallus*.
[src:french-navy/admiral] The 1818 edition of Samuel Johnson's *A Dictionary of the English Language*, edited and revised by the Rev.
[src:french-navy/admiral] The quote from John Minsheu's Dictionarie in Spanish and English (1599), given in Johnson's Dictionary, has been confirmed as being accurate.
[src:french-navy/admiral] Those Phanariots who attained the princely position of dragoman of the fleet served under the Ottoman admiral having administration of the Aegean islands and the Anatolian coast.
[src:french-navy/admiral] Central Command, introduced Vice Admiral Mark I.
[src:french-navy/admiral] One alternate etymology proposes that the term admiral evolved, instead, from the title of Amīr al-Umarāʾ (أمير الأمراء).
[src:french-navy/admiral] Under the reign of the Buyid dynasty (934 to 1062) of Iraq and Iran, the title of Amīr al-Umarāʾ, which means prince of princes, came to denote the heir-apparent, or crown prince.
[src:french-navy/admiral] This alternate etymology states that the term was in use for the Greco-Arab naval leaders (e.g.
[src:french-navy/admiral] Christodulus) in the Norman-Arab-Byzantine culture of Norman Sicily, which had formerly been ruled by Arabs, at least by the early 11th century.
[src:french-navy/admiral] During this time, the Norman Roger II of Sicily (1095–1154) employed a Greek Christian, known as George of Antioch, who previously had served as a naval commander for several North African Muslim rulers.
[src:french-navy/admiral] Roger styled George in Abbasid fashion as *Amir of Amirs*, or Amīr al-Umarāʾ, with the title becoming Latinized in the 13th century as *ammiratus ammiratorum*.
[src:french-navy/admiral] The Sicilians and later the Genoese took the first two parts of the term from their Aragon opponents and used them as one word, *amiral*. .
[src:french-navy/admiral] The French gave their sea commanders similar titles while in Portuguese and Spanish the word changed to *almirante*.
[src:french-navy/admiral] As the word was used by people speaking Latin or Latin-based languages it gained the "d" and endured a series of different endings and spellings leading to the English spelling *admyrall* in the 14th century and to *admiral* by the 16th century.
[src:french-navy/admiral] The etymology of a word does not suggest the antiquity of the word as it may have appeared in other languages with entirely different pronunciations.
[src:french-navy/admiral] The Greek ναύαρχος, for instance, which is pronounced "naúarkhos", existed from very ancient times in Greece.
[src:french-navy/admiral] The word "admiral" has come to be almost exclusively associated with the highest naval rank in most of the world's navies, equivalent to the army rank of general.
[src:french-navy/admiral] However, this was not always the case; for example, in some European countries prior to the end of World War II, admiral was the third highest naval rank after general admiral and grand admiral.
[src:french-navy/admiral] The rank of admiral has also been subdivided into various grades, several of which are historically extinct while others remain in use in most present-day navies.
[src:french-navy/admiral] The Royal Navy used the colours red, white, and blue, in descending order to indicate seniority of its admirals until 1864; for example, Horatio Nelson's highest rank was vice-admiral of the white.
[src:french-navy/admiral] The generic term for these naval equivalents of army generals is flag officer.
[src:french-navy/admiral] Some navies have also used army-type titles for them, such as the Cromwellian "general at sea".
[src:french-navy/admiral] While the rank is used in most of NATO countries, it is ranked differently depending on the country.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The **French Navy** is the maritime arm of the French Armed Forces and one of the four military service branches of France.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] It is among the largest and most powerful naval forces in the world recognised as being a blue-water navy.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The French Navy is capable of operating globally and conducting expeditionary missions, maintaining a significant overseas presence.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The French Navy is one of eight naval forces currently operating fixed-wing aircraft carriers, with its flagship *Charles de Gaulle* being the only nuclear-powered aircraft carrier outside the United States Navy, and one of two non-American vessels to use catapults to launch aircraft.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Founded in the 17th century, the French Navy is one of the oldest navies still in continuous service, with precursors dating back to the Middle Ages.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] It has taken part in key events in French history, including the Napoleonic Wars and both world wars, and played a critical role in establishing and securing the French colonial empire for over 400 years.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The French Navy pioneered several innovations in naval technology, including the first steam-powered ship of the line, first seagoing ironclad warship, first mechanically propelled submarine, first steel-hulled warship, and first armoured cruiser.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The French Navy consists of six main components: the Naval Action Force, the Submarine Forces (FOST and ESNA), French Naval Aviation, the Navy Riflemen (including Naval Commandos), the Marseille Naval Fire Battalion, and the Maritime Gendarmerie.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] As of 2021, the French Navy employed 44,000 personnel (37,000 military and 7,000 civilian), more than 180 ships, 200 aircraft, and six commandos units; as of 2014, its reserve element numbered roughly 48,000.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] It operates a wide range of fighting vessels, including various aeronaval forces, attack and ballistic missile submarines, frigates, patrol boats and support ships, with aircraft carrier *Charles de Gaulle* serving as the centrepiece of most expeditionary forces.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The first true French Royal Navy (French: *la Marine Royale*) was established in 1626 by Cardinal Richelieu, chief minister to King Louis XIII.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] During the French Revolution, *la Marine Royale* was formally renamed *la Marine Nationale*.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Under the First French Empire and the Second French Empire, the navy was designated as the Imperial French Navy (*la Marine impériale française*).
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Institutionally, however, the navy has never lost its short familiar nickname, *la Royale*.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The original symbol of the French Navy was a golden anchor, which, beginning in 1830, was interlaced by a sailing rope; this symbol was featured on all naval vessels, arms, and uniforms.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Cardinal Richelieu personally supervised the Navy until his death in 1643.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] He was succeeded by his protégé, Jean Baptiste Colbert, who introduced the first code of regulations of the French Navy and established the original naval dockyards in Brest and Toulon.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Colbert and his son, the Marquis de Seignelay, between them administered the Navy for twenty-nine years.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] During this century, the Navy cut its teeth in the Anglo-French War (1627–1629), the Franco-Spanish War (1635–59), the Second Anglo-Dutch War, the Franco-Dutch War, and the Nine Years' War.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Major battles in these years include the Battle of Augusta, Battle of Beachy Head, the Battles of Barfleur and La Hougue, the Battle of Lagos, and the Battle of Texel.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The 1700s opened with the War of the Spanish Succession, over a decade long, followed by the War of the Austrian Succession in the 1740s.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Principal engagements of these wars include the Battle of Vigo Bay and two separate Battles of Cape Finisterre in 1747.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The most grueling conflict for the Navy, however, was the Seven Years' War, in which it was virtually destroyed.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Significant actions include the Battle of Cap-Français, the Battle of Quiberon Bay, and another Battle of Cape Finisterre.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The Navy regrouped and rebuilt, and within 15 years it was eager to join the fray when France intervened in the American Revolutionary War.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Though outnumbered everywhere, the French fleets held the British at bay for years until victory.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] After this conflict and the concomitant Anglo-French War (1778–1783), the Navy emerged at a new height in its history.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Major battles in these years include the Battle of the Chesapeake, the Battle of Cape Henry, the Battle of Grenada, the invasion of Dominica, and three separate Battles of Ushant.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Within less than a decade, however, the Navy was decimated by the French Revolution when large numbers of veteran officers were dismissed or executed for their noble lineage.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Nonetheless, the Navy fought vigorously through the French Revolutionary Wars as well as the Quasi-War.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Significant actions include a fourth Battle of Ushant (known in English as the Glorious First of June), the Battle of Groix, the Atlantic campaign of May 1794, the French expedition to Ireland, the Battle of Tory Island, and the Battle of the Nile.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Other engagements of the Revolutionary Wars ensued in the early 1800s, including the Battle of the Malta Convoy and the Algeciras Campaign.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The Quasi-War wound down with single-ship actions including USS *Constellation* vs *La Vengeance* and USS *Enterprise* vs *Flambeau*.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] When Napoleon was crowned Emperor in 1804, he attempted to restore the Navy to a position that would enable his plan for an invasion of England.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] His dreams were dashed by the Battle of Trafalgar in 1805, where the British all but annihilated a combined Franco-Spanish fleet, a disaster that confirmed British naval superiority for the rest of the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Still, the Navy did not shrink from action: among the engagements of this time were the Battle of the Basque Roads, the Battle of Grand Port, the Mauritius campaign of 1809–1811, and the Battle of Lissa.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] After Napoleon's fall in 1815, the long era of Anglo-French rivalry on the seas began to close, and the Navy became more of an instrument for expanding the French colonial empire.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Under King Charles X, the two nations' fleets fought side by side in the Battle of Navarino, and throughout the rest of the century they generally behaved in a manner that paved the way for the Entente Cordiale.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Charles X sent a large fleet to execute the invasion of Algiers in 1830.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The next year, his successor, Louis Philippe I, made a show of force against Portugal at the Battle of the Tagus, and in 1838 conducted another display of gunboat diplomacy, this time in Mexico at the Battle of Veracruz.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Beginning in 1845, a five-year Anglo-French blockade of the Río de la Plata was imposed on Argentina over trade rights.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The Emperor Napoleon III was determined to follow an even stronger foreign policy than his predecessors, and the Navy was involved in a multitude of actions around the world.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] He joined in the Crimean War in 1854; major actions for the Navy include the siege of Petropavlovsk and the Battle of Kinburn.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The Navy was heavily involved in the Cochinchina Campaign in 1858, the Second Opium War in China, and the French intervention in Mexico.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] It took part in the French expedition to Korea and the Shimonoseki campaign.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] In the Franco-Prussian War in 1870, the Navy imposed an effective blockade of Germany, but events on land proceeded at such a rapid pace that it was superfluous.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Isolated engagements between French and German ships took place in other theaters, but the war was over in a matter of weeks.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The Navy continued to protect colonial safety and expansion under the French Third Republic.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The Sino-French War saw considerable naval action including the Battle of Fuzhou, the Battle of Shipu, and the Pescadores Campaign.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] In Vietnam, the Navy helped wage the Tonkin Campaign which included the Battle of Thuận An, and it later participated in the Franco-Siamese conflict of 1893.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The 19th century French Navy brought forth numerous new technologies.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] It led the development of naval artillery with its invention of the highly effective Paixhans gun.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] In 1850, *Napoléon* became the first steam-powered ship of the line in history, and *Gloire* became the first seagoing ironclad warship nine years later.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] In 1863, the Navy launched *Plongeur*, the first submarine in the world to be propelled by mechanical power.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] In 1876, *Redoutable* became the first steel-hulled warship ever.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] In 1887, *Dupuy de Lôme* became the world's first armoured cruiser.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] During the latter part of the century, French officers developed the so-called *Jeune École* (Young School) theory that emphasized the use of small, cheap torpedo boats to destroy expensive battleships, coupled with long-range commerce raiders to attack an opponent's merchant fleet.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The first seaplane, the French Fabre Hydravion, was flown in 1910, and the first seaplane carrier, *Foudre*, was christened in the following year.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Despite that innovation, the general development of the French Navy slowed down in the beginning of the 20th century as the Anglo-German naval arms race grew in intensity.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] It entered World War I with relatively few modern vessels, and during the war few warships were built because the main French effort was on land.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] While the British held control of the North Sea, the French held the Mediterranean, where they mostly kept watch on the Austro-Hungarian Navy.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The largest operations of the Navy were conducted during the Dardanelles Campaign.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] In December 1916, during the Noemvriana events, French warships also bombarded Athens, trying to force the pro-German government of Greece to change its policies.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The French Navy also played an important role in countering Germany's U-boat campaign by regularly patrolling the seas and escorting convoys.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Between the World Wars, the Navy modernized and expanded significantly, even in the face of limitations set by the 1922 Washington Naval Treaty.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] New additions included the heavy and fast *Fantasque*-class "super-destroyers", the *Richelieu*-class battleships, and the submarine *Surcouf* which was the largest and most powerful of its day.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] During the first two years of World War II, the French Navy participated in the Battle of the Atlantic, the Norwegian campaign, the Dunkirk evacuation and, briefly, the Battle of the Mediterranean.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] However, after the fall of France in June 1940, the Navy was obligated to remain neutral under the terms of the armistice that created Vichy France.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Approximately 100 French warships around the world joined the Free French under Charles de Gaulle, but the bulk of the French Navy, including all its capital ships, declared their allegiance to Vichy France.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] On 3 July 1940, Force H of the Royal Navy launched an attack on Mers-el-Kébir in Algeria to prevent the French fleet there from falling into German hands, destroying or damaging several French warships.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] In 1942, the Vichy Navy fought the Naval Battle of Casablanca when the Allies invaded French North Africa, but the confrontations were set aside once the Germans occupied Vichy France.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The capital ships were a primary target for the Germans, but before they could be seized they were scuttled by their own crews.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] A few small ships and submarines managed to escape in time, and these joined the Free French Naval Forces, an arm of Free France that fought as an adjunct of the Royal Navy until the end of the war.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] In the Pacific theatre as well, Free French vessels operated until the Japanese capitulation; *Richelieu* was present at the Japanese Instrument of Surrender.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The Navy later provided fire support and troop transport in the Indochina War, the Algerian War, the Gulf War, and the Kosovo War.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Since 2000, the Navy has given logistical support to the War in Afghanistan (2001–2021) as well as the global war on terror.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] In 2011, it assisted Opération Harmattan in Libya.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The chief of the naval staff is Amiral Nicolas Vaujour, and as of November 2024 the Navy has an active strength of 37,965 military personnel and 3,000 civilian staff.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] During most of the Cold War, the Navy was organised in two squadrons based in Brest and Toulon, commanded by ALESCLANT (*Amiral commandant l'escadre de l'Atlantique*) and ALESCMED (*Amiral commandant l'escadre de la Méditerranée*) respectively.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Since the post-Cold War restructuring process named Optimar '95, the two components have been divided into the Naval Action Force (commanded by ALFAN) and the Antisubmarine Group (commanded by ALGASM).
[src:french-navy/french-navy] As of 2014, the largest French naval base is the military port of Toulon.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Other major bases in metropolitan France are the Brest Arsenal and Île Longue on the Atlantic, and Cherbourg Naval Base on the English Channel.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Overseas French bases include Fort de France and Degrad des Cannes in the Americas; Port des Galets and Dzaoudzi in the Indian Ocean; and Nouméa and Papeete in the Pacific.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] In addition, the navy shares or leases bases in foreign locales such as Abu Dhabi, Dakar and Djibouti.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Although French naval doctrine calls for two aircraft carriers, the French only have one, *Charles de Gaulle*.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Originally a planned order for French aircraft carrier PA2 was based on the design of the British *Queen Elizabeth*-class aircraft carrier recently constructed and launched for the British Royal Navy.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] However, the French programme had been delayed several times for budgetary reasons and the result was priority being given to the more exportable FREMM project.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] In April 2013 it was confirmed that the second aircraft carrier project would be abandoned due to defence cuts announced in the 2013 French White Paper on Defence and National Security.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The French Navy operates three amphibious assault ships, eleven destroyers (classified in the French Navy as surface combatants of the "first rank"), five general purpose frigates and has a commitment to six fleet submarines (SSNs).
[src:french-navy/french-navy] These vessels, with the aircraft carrier *Charles de Gaulle*, constitute the French Navy's main ocean-going war-fighting force, while the four ballistic missile submarines (SSBN) of the navy's Strategic Oceanic Force provide the backbone of the French nuclear deterrent.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The French Naval Aviation is officially known as the *Aéronautique navale* and was created on the 19 June 1998 with the merging of Naval patrol aircraft and aircraft carrier squadrons.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] It has a strength of around 6,800 civilian and military personnel operating from four airbases in Metropolitan France.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The Aéronavale has been modernized with 41 Rafale fighters which operate from the aircraft carrier *Charles de Gaulle*.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Seamen must be at least 17 but no more than 30 years old, with no minimum level of schooling.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Petty officers must be at least 17 but no more than 30 years old, with at least a high school diploma giving access to university studies.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Petty officer candidates begin training with five months at the Petty Officer School of Maistrance at Brest.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Contract officers serve on an initial eight-year contract, renewable up to 20 years.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The rank insignia of the French Navy are worn on shoulder straps of shirts and white jackets, and on sleeves for navy jackets and mantels.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Until 2005, only commissioned officers had an anchor on their insignia, but enlisted personnel are now receiving them as well.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Commanding officers have titles of *capitaine*, but are called *commandant* (in the army, both *capitaine* and *commandant* are ranks, which tends to stir some confusion among the public).
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The two highest ranks, *vice-amiral d'escadre* and *amiral* (admiral), are functions, rather than ranks.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] They are assumed by officers ranking *vice-amiral* (vice admiral).
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The only *amiral de la flotte* (Admiral of the Fleet) was François Darlan after he was refused the dignity of *amiral de France* (Admiral of France).
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Equivalent to the dignity of Marshal of France, the rank of *amiral de France* remains theoretical in the Fifth Republic; it was last granted in 1869, during the Second Empire, but retained during the Third Republic until the death of its bearer in 1873.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The title of *amiral de la flotte* was created so that Darlan would not have an inferior rank than his counterpart in the British Royal Navy, who had the rank of Admiral of the Fleet.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The rank insignia of commissioned officers.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The rank insignia of non-commissioned officers and enlisted personnel.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Unlike in the French Army and Air and Space Force, one does not prepend *mon* to the name of the rank when addressing an officer (that is, not *mon capitaine,* but simply *capitaine*).
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The main military musical unit of the French Navy is the Military Band of the Toulon Fleet (French: *La musique des équipages de la flotte de Toulon*), founded on 13 July 1827.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The Bagad Lann Bihoue, based on the bagad bands in Bretagne, is currently the sole pipe band in the service of the French Navy, which uses bagpipes and bombards, and thus is affiliated to the band.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] In Canada, French naval music has affected the traditions of Canadian navy bands.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] French navy bands in the country date back to the era of New France.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Musical units were primarily attached to the Compagnies Franches de la Marine and the Troupes de la marine, the former of which maintained two drums (tambour) and a fife.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] France's financial problems have affected all branches of her military.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The 2013 French White Paper on Defence and National Security cancelled the long-planned new aircraft carrier and a possible fourth *Mistral*-class amphibious assault ship.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The backbone of the fleet will be the *Aquitaine*-class FREMM anti-submarine frigates, replacing the *Georges Leygues* class, but plans to buy a possible seventeen FREMMs were cut back to eleven and then to eight.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The cancellation of the third and fourth Horizon destroyers meant that the last two FREMM hulls, which entered service between 2021 and 2023, are fitted out as FREDA air-defence ships to replace the *Cassard* class.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] DCNS has shown a FREMM-ER concept to meet this requirement, emphasising ballistic missile defence with the Thales Sea Fire 500 AESA radar.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] With respect to support ships, the *Durance* class are being replaced under the FLOTLOG project by up to four derivatives of Italy's *Vulcano*-class logistic support ship, with three being delivered from 2023 to 2027.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] A fourth potential ship is delayed until after 2030.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Construction has started on the first of six *Barracuda*-class nuclear attack submarines; commissioning of *Suffren* took place in 2020.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] These nuclear attack submarines are to be followed in the 2030s by the incremental introduction of a new class of nuclear-powered ballistic missile submarines (SSBNs) whose construction began in 2024.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] The first MM40 Exocet Block 3 missile was test-fired in 2010 to be produced.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Naval versions of the *SCALP EG* land-attack cruise missile are under development, along with a planned Aster Block 1NT with greater capabilities against ballistic missiles.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] In October 2018, the French Ministry of Defence launched an 18-month study for €40 million for the eventual future replacement of the aircraft carrier *Charles de Gaulle* beyond 2030.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] A decision to build the new carrier was taken by President Emmanuel Macron in 2020 and once it enters service it is anticipated to remain in service until beyond 2080.
[src:french-navy/french-navy] Construction of the new carrier is to begin in around 2025 with service entry anticipated in the latter 2030s.
